# Component Rules

## File Structure
Every component lives in its own folder:
```
ComponentName/
  ComponentName.tsx           # implementation
  ComponentName.module.scss   # styles (BEM)
  ComponentName.test.tsx      # tests
  ComponentName.types.ts      # types reused outside this file (optional)
  ComponentName.utils.ts      # pure logic extracted from component (optional)
  index.ts                    # barrel export
```
Add `ComponentName.types.ts` only when types are shared with other files.
Add `ComponentName.utils.ts` only when there is non-trivial logic to extract.

## Props
- Use `type`, never `interface`
- Extend the relevant HTML element attributes type where it makes sense
- Spread `...rest` onto the root element so consumers can pass `data-*`, `aria-*`, `className`, etc.
- Always accept an optional `className` prop and merge it with `cn()`

```tsx
// ✅
type ButtonProps = ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> & {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
};

export const Button = ({ variant = 'primary', className, ...rest }: ButtonProps) => (
  <button className={cn(styles.button, styles[`button--${variant}`], className)} {...rest} />
);
```

## Extracting Logic
Move logic out of the component when it grows complex:

```
// Pure transforms / calculations → ComponentName.utils.ts
export const buildClassName = (variant: string, size: string) => ...

// Stateful logic / side effects → useComponentName.ts (in src/hooks/ or co-located)
export const useDropdown = (items: Item[]) => { ... return { isOpen, toggle, ... }; };
```

### Hooks placement

Decide where a hook lives based on its intended scope:

- Component-scoped hooks — when the hook is specific to a single component's behavior (keyboard handling, open/close state tied to component internals, derived selection logic), colocate it inside the component folder alongside the component, styles, and tests:

```
ComponentName/
  ComponentName.tsx
  ComponentName.module.scss
  useComponentName.ts         # component-scoped hook
  useComponentName.test.ts    # tests for the component hook
  ComponentName.utils.ts
  ComponentName.types.ts
  index.ts
```

- Generic/shared hooks — when the hook is reusable across multiple components or pages (form helpers, generic event listeners, window-size, debouncing utilities), put it in `src/hooks/` with its tests:

```
src/hooks/
  useDebounce.ts
  useDebounce.test.ts
  useDisclosure.ts
  useDisclosure.test.ts
```

Co-locating component-scoped hooks keeps implementation details next to the UI they support and simplifies refactoring; keeping generic hooks in `src/hooks/` makes them discoverable for reuse.

## Composition — layout & UI primitives
Reuse shared components instead of duplicating flex layouts, raw buttons, or inline SVGs.

| Primitive | Use when |
|---|---|
| `Container` | Constraining page/content width |
| `Stack` | Column or row layout with token `gap`, `align`, or `justify`; use `as` for semantic elements (`nav`, `header`, `footer`, `section`, `ul`, `li`) |
| `Button` | Any clickable action; `variant="ghost"` + `iconOnly` for dismiss/nav icon buttons |
| `Icon` | Lucide icons; pass `variant` for standalone semantic color, omit inside `Button` |
| `EmptyState` etc. | Composite patterns in `src/components/patterns/` — built from primitives above |

```tsx
// ✅ form field wrapper — Stack replaces flex-column + gap in SCSS
<Stack gap="1" className={styles['input__wrapper']}>
  {label && <label …>{label}</label>}
  <input … />
  {helperText && <span …>{helperText}</span>}
</Stack>

// ✅ icon-only control — Button + Icon, not a raw <button> + inline SVG
<Button variant="ghost" size="sm" iconOnly aria-label="Close">
  <Icon icon={X} size="sm" />
</Button>

// ✅ semantic layout — Stack `as` avoids an extra wrapper
<Stack as="header" direction="row" justify="between" align="center">…</Stack>

// ❌ bespoke flex wrapper in SCSS when Stack fits
.input__wrapper { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: $spacing-1; }

// ❌ one-off icon button styling
<button className={styles.close}><X /></button>
```

Use `Stack` `as` for semantic elements (`nav`, `header`, `footer`, `section`, `ul`, `li`) instead of nesting a raw element inside Stack. Keep native `<button>` for calendar day cells and other controls that aren't layout wrappers. Do not replace grid-based or absolutely positioned layouts with `Stack`.

## Styling — SCSS Modules + BEM
- Never use inline styles or CSS-in-JS
- Use `cn()` from `@/utils/cn` for conditional class merging
- Follow BEM strictly: `.block`, `.block__element`, `.block--modifier`
- Consume design tokens via `@use '@/styles/tokens/...' as *`
- Use CSS custom properties for theme-aware values

```scss
// ✅ BEM
.button { }
.button--primary { }
.button--sm { }
.button__icon { }

// ❌ non-BEM
.primaryButton { }
.btn-sm { }
```

## Transitions
Add transitions where they improve perceived quality (hover, focus, open/close states).
- **Never** use `transition: all` — list only the properties that change
- Prefer short durations (100–200ms) for interactive feedback, longer (250–350ms) for layout shifts

```scss
// ✅
transition: background-color 150ms ease, box-shadow 150ms ease;

// ❌
transition: all 200ms ease;
```

## Accessibility
- Add `aria-*` attributes whenever the semantic role or state is not obvious from the HTML alone
- Common cases: `aria-expanded`, `aria-controls`, `aria-label`, `aria-current`, `aria-disabled`, `aria-live`
- Interactive elements must have a visible `:focus-visible` outline
- Form inputs must have an associated `<label>` via `htmlFor` + `id`
- Use semantic HTML before reaching for `role` overrides

```tsx
// ✅
<button aria-expanded={isOpen} aria-controls="menu-list">Toggle</button>
<ul id="menu-list" role="menu"> ... </ul>
```

## Testing
- One test file per component, co-located in the same folder
- **Hooks must have tests too** (`hookName.test.ts` in `src/hooks/`)
- Use `@testing-library/react` + `vitest`
- Test behaviour (what the user sees/does), not implementation details
- Cover: renders correctly · user interactions · disabled/error states · aria attributes · variant/size classes

```tsx
// ✅
it('sets aria-expanded when open', async () => {
  render(<Dropdown items={items} />);
  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button'));
  expect(screen.getByRole('button')).toHaveAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
});
```
